r watersheds of origin. Attentive to both the economic context of industrial food production and the materiality of human-animal relations, this book highlights the fragile and contingent relational practices that constitute salmon aquaculture and the multiple ways of "becoming salmon" that emerge as a result.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aSalmon farmingxSocial aspects. 0aSalmon farming. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311062111208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520961838423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520961838.jpg  a978-3-11-062111-2  UC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-065748-7  UCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles